thesis that a significant fraction of cells in aquatic ecosystems are inactive. Bacterioplankton production rates ranged from {\textless}0.05 to 2.8 mg C m‚àí3 day‚àí1. Growth rates ranged from {\textless}0.05 to 0.25 day‚àí1, implying turnover rates of 2.5 to {\textgreater}200 days. Our results demonstrate that bacterioplankton and viruses are dynamic but ubiquitous features of Arctic microbial communities. The contribution of bacteria and viruses to Arctic food webs is discussed.},
