	abstract = {Freshwater and marine environments constitute the largest global reservoirs of the greenhouse gas methane (CH4) and natural abundance radiocarbon measurements (14C-CH4) can allow for high confidence interpretations about CH4 dynamics operating in these environments. Collecting sufficient amounts of CH4 sample for a standard, high precision 14C-accelerator mass spectrometry (AMS) analysis (‚àº 200 Œºg carbon (C)) was previously unfeasible when sampling from low CH4 concentration waters, such as much of the surface ocean (‚àº 2 nM), which would require collecting the CH4 from 8500 L of seawater. The method described here involves pumping 20,000‚Äì40,000 L of seawater up from depth through a dissolved gas extraction system, which enables the collection of a sample composed of 100s of L of gas in less than 4 h on station. The large volume extracted gas sample is compressed into a 1.7 L cylinder for transport from the ship to the home laboratory. The home laboratory preparation of each sample to a CH4-derived carbon dioxide aliquot for 14C-AMS analysis is carried out in 3 h on a flow-through vacuum line that simultaneously prepares aliquots for stable isotope analyses (Œ¥13C-CH4 and Œ¥2H-CH4). The total process blank of the method is small (5.0 Œºg CH4-C) and composes 1.2\% of the average collected and prepared sample (424 ¬± 163 Œºg, from a recent campaign; n = 16). The 14C-CH4 blanks prepared on the vacuum line have acceptably low 14C content (0.23 ¬± 0.07 percent Modern Carbon (pMC); n = 7) relative to the 14C-dead (0 pMC) CH4 from which they are prepared.},
