	abstract = {Acoustic waves expanding out from a controlled sound source shot during a marine seismic survey are reflected off from subsurface interfaces where changes in the seawater density and velocity of the sound are significant. Density compensating, fine-scale (1‚Äì10-m thick) temperature-salinity contrasts in the water column result in small changes in sound speed and appear as distinct reflector layers, if processing gains are sufficiently high. Recent studies image low-frequency (10‚Äì150Hz) returns that are specular reflections from laterally continuous steps or sheets in the ocean‚Äôs temperature-depth structure. With the very dense lateral sampling of reflection profiling (order 10m), exceptional detail can be seen in the structure of oceanic reflectors throughout portions of the water column. Spectacular images of thermohaline fine structure in the ocean include features such as intrusions, internal waves, and mesoscale eddies. The discovery of seismic reflections from the water column and the ability to image large volumes of the ocean at full depth and at high lateral resolution opens up new possibilities for probing the structure of the ocean.},
