	abstract = {The branched glycerol dialkyl glycerol tetraethers (brGDGTs) can be produced in situ under methanotrophic/hypoxic conditions in lakes. However, the effect of dynamic methanotrophic activities in the widely-distributed seafloor methane seeps on brGDGTs distributions in global continent margins remains enigmatic. In this study, we firstly report the occurrence of in situ produced brGDGTs in cold seep environments, based on the analysis of tetraether lipid distributions in the authigenic carbonates collected from the northern section of the Okinawa Trough (OT). The abundance ratio of isoGDGTs to brGDGTs (Ri/b) was much lower in the authigenic carbonates (0.94 to 2.25) than in the adjacent normal marine sediments ({\textgreater}10) and suspended particulate matter ({\textgreater}60) in the East China Sea (ECS). Such significant higher bacterial branched GDGTs ratios in the authigenic carbonates indicate its additional sources besides terrestrial and/or water column inputs. Specifically, the brGDGT (Ia), brGDGT (IIa) and brGDGT (IIa‚Äô) appear to form in situ in cold seeps, and are influenced by the methane flux significantly as indicated by the fractional abundances of GDGTs along the transect of pipes, network analysis, and correlations between Methane Index (MI) and brGDGTs. Our study highlights that the distributions of seafloor methane seeps could impact the bacterial tetraether lipid distributions in ocean, which would hamper the universal application of brGDGT-based proxies for terrigenous organic carbon tracing and paleoclimate reconstruction in marine environments.},
