	abstract = {The subtropical South Pacific Gyre (SPG) encompasses the largest oligotrophic region of the global ocean. In these remote waters dissolved organic matter (DOM) accumulates in the surface waters, though constituting a potential source of nutrients and energy to sustain microbial life. On a zonal transect across the SPG, we quantified bulk dissolved organic carbon (DOC) and assessed the DOM composition via ultrahigh resolution mass spectrometry (UHR-MS) of solid-phase extracted DOC (SPE-DOC) to elucidate the molecular-level reasons behind the apparent recalcitrance of the DOM prevailing in the SPG. We included a comparison between two individual formula assignment approaches to UHR-MS data in absorption and magnitude mode which yielded consistent results.},
