	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong class="journal-contentHeaderColor"{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} Accurate assessment of anthropogenic carbon dioxide (CO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) emissions and their redistribution among the atmosphere, ocean, and terrestrial biosphere in a changing climate is critical to better understand the global carbon cycle, support the development of climate policies, and project future climate change. Here we describe and synthesize datasets and methodology to quantify the five major components of the global carbon budget and their uncertainties. Fossil CO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} emissions ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{E}$_{\textrm{FOS}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) are based on energy statistics and cement production data, while emissions from land-use change ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{E}$_{\textrm{LUC}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}), mainly deforestation, are based on land use and land-use change data and bookkeeping models. Atmospheric CO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} concentration is measured directly, and its growth rate ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{G}$_{\textrm{ATM}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) is computed from the annual changes in concentration. The ocean CO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} sink ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{S}$_{\textrm{OCEAN}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) is estimated with global ocean biogeochemistry models and observation-based data products. The terrestrial CO{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{2}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} sink ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{S}$_{\textrm{LAND}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) is estimated with dynamic global vegetation models. The resulting carbon budget imbalance ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{B}$_{\textrm{IM}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}), the difference between the estimated total emissions and the estimated changes in the atmosphere, ocean, and terrestrial biosphere, is a measure of imperfect data and understanding of the contemporary carbon cycle. All uncertainties are reported as {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}¬±{\textless}/span{\textgreater}1{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{œÉ}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}. For the first time, an approach is shown to reconcile the difference in our {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{E}$_{\textrm{LUC}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} estimate with the one from national greenhouse gas inventories, supporting the assessment of collective countries' climate progress.{\textless}/p{\textgreater} {\textless}p{\textgreater}For the year 2020, {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{E}$_{\textrm{FOS}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} declined by 5.4 \% relative to 2019, with fossil emissions at 9.5 {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}¬±{\textless}/span{\textgreater} 0.5 GtC yr{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{‚àí1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} (9.3 {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}¬±{\textless}/span{\textgreater} 0.5 GtC yr{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{‚àí1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} when the cement carbonation sink is included), and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}\textit{E}$_{\textrm{LUC}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} was 0.9 {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}¬±{\textless}/span{\textgreater} 0.7 GtC yr{\textless}span class="